---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL
const dg = (name: string) => `${base}images/${name}.svg`
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>Isobenefit Urbanism: QGIS Plugin</h1>
  <h6>Brainstorming walkable urban growth on real-world data</h6>

  <section>
    <p>
      The <strong>Isobenefit Urbanism</strong> plugin for QGIS simulates how a place could grow so that
      everyone keeps walkable access to <strong>both</strong> mixed-use local centres (shops and services
      among homes) <strong>and</strong> green space. From the simulation it generates <strong>idealised planning scenarios</strong> for further discussion
      with planning experts. It runs on your own GIS layers, and it is meant for exploring options rather than
      prescribing them.
    </p>
    <figure id="hero-plan">
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_recommended_plan')} alt="An idealised scenario for Cambourne: new settlements with walkable centres woven through a green matrix around the existing town" />
      <figcaption>An idealised scenario for <strong>Cambourne</strong>, grown from the downloaded layers shown
      below. New settlements, coloured by density from pale (low) to deep (high), with their mixed-use centres
      in red, join the existing town (muted taupe), and every home stays within a walk of a centre and of
      green. The same example is used throughout this page.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <nav class="toc">
      <a href="#concept">Concept</a>
      <a href="#inputs">Data</a>
      <a href="#grid">From layers to cells</a>
      <a href="#simulation">The simulation</a>
      <a href="#plan">From runs to a scenario</a>
      <a href="#postprocessing">Post-processing</a>
      <a href="#outputs">Outputs</a>
      <a href="#scenarios">Parameters</a>
      <a href="#departures">Departures</a>
      <a href="#credits">Credits</a>
    </nav>
  </section>

  <h2 id="concept">Concept &amp; rationale</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      <a href="https://lucadacci.wixsite.com/dacci/isobenefit-urbanism-morphogenesis">Isobenefit Urbanism</a>
      (Luca D'Acci) describes a city whose benefits are spread <em>evenly</em>; the <em>iso</em> means
      equal. Wherever you live, and however large the settlement grows, you can walk both to a local centre
      and to green land, so quality of life does not depend on which part of town you live in. The aim is
      to avoid <strong>sprawl</strong>, which strands people far from centres and paves over nature, and
      equally to avoid <strong>overcrowding</strong>, which squeezes nature out.
    </p>
    <p>
      It also sits between master-planning and laissez-faire growth: a few simple rules <em>guide</em>
      development, while the detailed form is left to emerge. The plugin works the same way: a
      <strong>cellular-automaton</strong> simulation grows a grid of land cells step by step under rules that
      keep new development within a walk of a centre and protect green corridors. The rules include randomness, so there
      is no single answer; the plugin runs many simulations and reports the <strong>variation</strong>
      across them, as well as coherent individual <strong>scenarios</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The settlements and their centres should also be linked by effective public transport, buses and
      rail. Without that link they would not work as one cohesive city, and dispersed development becomes a
      warning sign rather than a feature. The plugin downloads streets, stops and stations as groundwork
      for this.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="using">Using the plugin</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      This page explains the model, using one real town throughout. To install the plugin and
      run it yourself, the <a href={`${base}plugin/`}>plugin guide</a> covers installation, a first-run
      walkthrough, every dialog control, the outputs and troubleshooting. Ready-made places to start
      from, with data and parameters prepared, are in the
      <a href={`${base}scenarios/`}>scenario library</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="inputs">Step 1: Download the data</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      A companion <strong>Extract from OpenStreetMap</strong> tool downloads all of the input layers for an
      area of interest, so no manual data preparation is needed. The downloaded layers are ordinary editable
      layers, though: you can adjust them before running a simulation, or use your own layers instead. The
      panels below are <strong>the downloaded layers</strong> for a 4.2 km window around Cambourne, fetched
      with the plugin's own queries. Each panel shows one layer of the same place, so green does not overlap built land,
      centres sit inside the built fabric, and when the layers are stacked they add back up to the whole
      town.
    </p>
    <div class="layer-grid">
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_extents')} alt="" /><figcaption>The extents layer sets the area of interest. It is the only layer the simulation requires.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_built')} alt="" /><figcaption>The existing built fabric. The simulation treats it as frozen and never redevelops it.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_green')} alt="" /><figcaption>Existing green space, which the growth rules preserve.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_centres')} alt="" /><figcaption>Mixed-use urban centres, taken from retail and commercial land. Every cell they cover acts as a centre.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_unbuildable')} alt="" /><figcaption>Unbuildable land: water, industrial land, and buffered barrier corridors such as the A428.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_industrial')} alt="" /><figcaption>Industrial land. It stays as it is, but no new housing is placed on it.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_streets')} alt="" /><figcaption>The street network, classed by road type. It lays the groundwork for walking-distance routing.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_pt')} alt="" /><figcaption>Public-transport stops, collected for future transit-aware growth.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Two further datasets, <em>railways</em> and <em>rail/tram stations</em>, are also downloaded. They
      are empty here because Cambourne has no railway. Where stations do exist, they anchor centres in the
      scenarios.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('input_composite')} alt="All downloaded layers stacked into one map of Cambourne" />
      <figcaption>All of the layers together. Throughout this page, vector shapes show <em>data</em> and
      dots show the <em>simulation</em>.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="grid">Step 2: From layers to cells</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      In QGIS you point the run dialog at these layers, choose a projected CRS and an output path, and press
      Run; the rest is automatic. The simulation works on a grid (here 50 m cells), so the vector layers are
      rasterised first: existing built fabric becomes <em>frozen</em> built cells, downloaded green becomes
      protected green cells, centre <em>areas</em> become centre cells across their full extent, and water,
      industrial land and buffered motorway-class corridors are marked <strong>unbuildable</strong>, so the
      simulation never develops them. Every run on this page starts from this grid:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_substrate')} alt="Cambourne rasterised to the simulation grid" />
      <figcaption>The town as cells. The taupe dots are the existing built fabric, the magenta dots its
      existing centres, and the blue dots are unbuildable cells; the A428 corridor and the waterways stand
      out. The small green dots are free land, and the real street network stays visible beneath.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="simulation">Step 3: The simulation</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Each step, the cellular automaton visits the land grid and decides whether an undeveloped cell may be
      built. The rules are shown below, zoomed into a schematic neighbourhood.
    </p>
    <div class="ca-step">
      <h4>Step 0: population target</h4>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_0')} alt="Step 0: population target" /><figcaption>The population is counted once per iteration, after every cell has been visited, not partway through. A whole iteration always runs to completion, so the simulation stops only before the next one begins once the target is reached, and the final population can slightly overshoot.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <div class="ca-step">
      <h4>Step 1: a candidate cell</h4>
      <p>A cell is only a candidate if it is empty <em>and</em> on the periphery of built land:</p>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1a')} alt="" /><figcaption>This cell is already built, so there is nothing to do and it is skipped.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1b')} alt="" /><figcaption>This cell is empty but touches no built land, so it is not on the periphery and is skipped.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1c')} alt="" /><figcaption>This cell is empty and touches built land, so it is a candidate and the checks continue.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <div class="ca-step">
      <h4>Step 2: centre walk</h4>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_2')} alt="Step 2: centre walk" /><figcaption>The candidate must be within a <em>centre walk</em> of a centrality, which keeps new homes near a centre.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <div class="ca-step">
      <h4>Step 3: green span</h4>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_3')} alt="Step 3: green span" /><figcaption>The same candidate sits on a green corridor. Building it narrows the corridor from 500 m to 400 m, which still meets the <em>minimum green span</em>, so the check passes.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <div class="ca-step">
      <h4>Step 4: build</h4>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_4')} alt="Step 4: build" /><figcaption>If every check passes, the cell is built, and the population it houses counts toward the target.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Two green settings play different roles. The <em>minimum green span</em> above is a building rule; the
      simulation refuses to pinch a green corridor below that width. The <em>green walk</em> sets how far a
      home may be from usable green, and it is judged on the finished scenario alongside the centre walk.
    </p>
    <h3>Where new centres come from</h3>
    <p>
      As built land outgrows a walk of any centre, the simulation seeds a new <em>neighbouring</em> centre,
      which lets a single town keep growing outward. A separate control, the <strong>Dispersed
      development</strong> control (Off, Moderate or Aggressive), sets how readily development
      <em>leapfrogs</em> away from the core to form satellite settlements.
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_neighbouring')} alt="" /><figcaption>A <em>neighbouring</em> centre is seeded where built land has outgrown a walk of every existing centre.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_isolated')} alt="" /><figcaption>An <em>isolated</em> centre lets a satellite settlement leapfrog away from the core.</figcaption></figure>
    <h3>The rules at work on the real town</h3>
    <p>
      Below, those rules run on the Cambourne grid from step 2; the three figures show the same run at three
      points in time. New development (coloured by density) stays on the periphery of the existing fabric,
      keeps within a walk of a centre (red seeds appear as the town outgrows them), and leaves the green
      corridors and the unbuildable cells alone.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="wide" src={dg('demo_growth')} alt="The growth rules at work on Cambourne, at iterations 6 and 30 and once the target is met" />
      <figcaption>The same run at three points: first infill at the edges (iteration 6), settlements consolidating with new centres seeded (iteration 30), and the raw grown state once the target is met.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Two further settings shape growth. The <strong>build probability</strong> is the per-step growth rate;
      lower values grow tighter and more compact, higher values faster and looser. The <strong>development
      density</strong> is set as three tiers, low, medium and high people per km², each with a probability,
      and the three probabilities sum to 1. Every new cell is built at one of the three densities, drawn at
      those probabilities, so the probabilities set the mix. Growth counts new development only, and stops
      once the new population reaches the target; the existing fabric is context and is not counted. The
      finished scenario then arranges the drawn densities and colours the plan by tier, described in step 5.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="plan">Step 4: From many runs to one scenario</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      A single run is one plausible outcome; a different random seed gives a different, equally valid
      layout. So the plugin runs an <strong>ensemble</strong> and does two things with it. First, it blends
      every run into a development-<strong>likelihood</strong> map, the real probabilities over Cambourne,
      from twenty-four runs.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_likelihood')} alt="Development likelihood over Cambourne from 24 blended runs" />
      <figcaption>Each cell's shade is the share of runs in which it ends up built: dark where growth is
      robust, faint where it is contingent. This is an uncertainty map, not itself a buildable layout.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Because a probability surface is not a buildable layout, the plugin also picks out the single best
      run, the one with the shortest average walk to amenities, and carries that forward.
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_select')} alt="" /><figcaption>A probability surface is not a buildable layout, so the single best run is picked out: the one with the shortest average walk to amenities.</figcaption></figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="postprocessing">Step 5: Post-processing the chosen run</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The chosen run is refined into the idealised scenario. Post-processing deliberately changes <strong>only
      the centres</strong>, plus a limited building cleanup; the buildings themselves come from the
      simulation.
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_cleanup')} alt="" /><figcaption>In the cleanup, stranded settlements below the minimum size revert to green. The raw state is saved as well, so the change stays visible.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_centring')} alt="" /><figcaption>A grown centre often lands on the edge or in a corner of its development, where it serves fewer homes. Each is moved to a <em>central</em> spot in the same built area.</figcaption></figure>
    <p>
      The centres are mixed-use throughout: a centre cell keeps its homes and gains shops and services, and
      each centre is sized by the population it serves at a rule-of-thumb provision (m² of centre land per
      person). Once the centres are settled, each scenario is coloured by <strong>density tier</strong>. The
      densities drawn during the run are arranged by walking distance to the final centres: the highest sit
      nearest a centre, then medium, then low. The mix of tiers is fixed, so the total population does not
      change; only their placement is set here. Arranging it after post-processing, rather than during
      growth, means the placement measures against the centres the scenario actually shows, not against
      whichever centres happened to exist mid-run.
    </p>
    <p>
      Finally, centres are offered at two <strong>clustering</strong> strengths. The run and the buildings
      are the same; only the centre arrangement differs. These are the two options the plugin writes:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="wide" src={dg('demo_clustering')} alt="Two centre-clustering options for the same run: moderately clustered and tightly clustered" />
      <figcaption>The same run and buildings at two centre spacings: moderately clustered gives more, smaller centres and shorter walks; tightly clustered gives fewer, larger, more consolidated centres.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Either can be compared against the raw grown state at the end of <a href="#simulation">step 3</a>. The
      raw state is always saved alongside, so everything post-processing did stays visible.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="outputs">Step 6: Outputs</h2>
  <section>
    <p>An ensemble run writes a small set of layers, each shown above:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>existing development</strong>, the starting grid from <a href="#grid">step 2</a></li>
      <li><strong>raw (before post-processing)</strong>, the chosen run as it grew (the end of <a href="#simulation">step 3</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>moderately and tightly clustered centres</strong>, the two scenario options from <a href="#postprocessing">step 5</a>, each coloured by density tier</li>
      <li><strong>development likelihood</strong> for built and for green, the uncertainty map from <a href="#plan">step 4</a></li>
      <li><strong><code>_report.txt</code></strong>, a record of the parameters and the per-option statistics</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Reading the report: every population figure counts <strong>new residents only</strong>. Existing
      fabric is shown for context and is assumed to be served by its own centres, so it is never counted.
      The per-person readouts follow the same convention: <em>m² of centre per person</em> is new mixed-use
      centre land over new residents, and <em>m² of walkable green per person</em> is new green over new
      residents. The coverage percentages, by contrast, include every home, existing and new, since a walk
      to a centre matters to everyone.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <em>single</em> run, with the ensemble checkbox off, is instead written step by step as a growth
      animation you can play in the QGIS Temporal Controller. The three growth moments in
      <a href="#simulation">step 3</a> are three such frames.
    </p>
    <p>
      The figure <a href="#hero-plan">at the top of the page</a> is the moderately-clustered scenario
      from this pipeline.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Changing the parameters</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Every figure below is a <strong>complete pipeline run on the same Cambourne grid</strong>; only the named
      parameter changes between figures.
    </p>

    <h3>Dispersed development</h3>
    <p>
      This control sets how readily growth leapfrogs away from the existing fabric. Even <em>Moderate</em>
      keeps the existing town dominant, while <em>Aggressive</em> scatters satellites across the window.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_off')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Off.</strong> Growth happens only at the edges of the existing fabric.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_moderate')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Moderate.</strong> The town leads, and a few satellites appear.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_aggressive')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Aggressive.</strong> Satellites scatter across the whole window.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>

    <h3>Build probability</h3>
    <p>This is the per-step growth rate. Over the same number of steps, faster growth reaches much further.</p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_slow')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Slow (0.08).</strong> Growth stays tight and compact.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_fast')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Fast (0.6).</strong> Far more is grown in the same time.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="departures">Departures from standard Isobenefit Urbanism</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The growth rules themselves (periphery-only development, a walk to the nearest centrality, protected
      green spans, stochastic seeding of new centralities) follow D'Acci's morphogenesis and Voto's original
      simulator. Around that core, this implementation departs in several ways, listed here to keep the boundary
      with the theory clear:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Ensembles instead of a single run.</strong> The original simulator produces a single run.
        We run many, blend them into likelihood layers, and select the best single run by shortest average
        walk to amenities.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Post-processing of the chosen run.</strong> The original keeps centres exactly where they
        seeded. We add a limited cleanup (stranded fragments below a minimum settlement size revert to green) and
        re-position the mixed-use centres to the interior of the development they serve, sized by the
        population in their catchment at a m²-per-person rule of thumb, and offered at two clustering
        strengths. The raw grown state is always saved alongside, so the edit is transparent.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Density tiers arranged toward centres.</strong> The original draws each block's density
        randomly from three fixed tiers, scattered across the map. We keep the three tiers and their
        probabilities, but arrange the drawn densities in post-processing so the highest sit nearest the
        mixed-use centres, then medium, then low. The mix is unchanged, so the population is the same; only
        the placement is organised. Growth counts new development only.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Separate centre-walk and green-walk thresholds.</strong> The original uses one walkable
        radius; we let each amenity have its own, and score the finished plan against both.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Real-data grounding.</strong> Existing fabric is frozen (never redeveloped); water,
        industrial land and motorway-class corridors are carved out as unbuildable; downloaded centre
        <em>areas</em> act as true multi-cell centres; and an OSM extraction tool supplies all of it. When a
        street network is supplied, post-processing measures walking distances along it and stations anchor
        centres; the growth rules themselves do not use streets or stops yet.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h2 id="credits">Credits &amp; sources</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Based on the <a href="https://lucadacci.wixsite.com/dacci/isobenefit-urbanism-morphogenesis">Isobenefit
      Urbanism</a> concept by Luca D'Acci, with original
      <a href="https://github.com/mitochevole/isobenefit-cities">Python code</a> by Michele Voto. Developed as
      part of the Future Urban Growth project at <strong>UCL Bartlett School of Planning</strong> (Tommaso
      Gabrieli, Luca D'Acci, Heeseo Kwon, Stephen Marshall, Valentina Marin Maureira, Gareth Simons). The
      code lives at <a href="https://github.com/UCL/BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin">BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The example data is map data © <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright">OpenStreetMap</a>
      contributors, available under the Open Database Licence (ODbL).
    </p>
    <p>Further reading:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        D'Acci, L. (2019). <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jenvman.2019.05.129">A new type of cities for
